    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-11-03T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-11-03T05:00:00-05:00" n="380"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d380">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.00/11–354: Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 380<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Republic of China (<persName
                            corresp="#p_RKL1" type="from">Rankin</persName>) to the <gloss type="to"
                            >Department of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret<lb/>priority</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Taipei</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-11-03T18:00:00+08:00"
                            >November 3, 1954—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>325. Taipei’s 318.<note n="1" xml:id="d380fn1">
                        <ref target="#d374">Document 374</ref>.</note> As <persName
                        corresp="#p_CMGWC1">General Chase</persName> has reported in detail through
                    military channels, Chinese Air Force attacked point near Tung An some 14 miles
                    north of Amoy Island at approximately same time Communists raided Tachen
                    November 1. <gloss target="#t_CAF1">CAF</gloss> raid by 9 or 10 F–47s (of which
                    one lost) was without prior consultation with <gloss target="#t_MAAG1"
                        >MAAG</gloss>. Timing was such that neither raid could qualify as
                    retaliation for other. It is reported, however, that Peiping radio admitted
                    Tachen raid preceded that on Tung An which should largely nullify any complaint
                    Reds might raise.</p>
                <pb facs="0882" n="854" xml:id="pg_854"/>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_CMGWC1">Chase</persName> is addressing letter to Chief of
                    General Staff<note n="2" xml:id="d380fn2">The letter from <persName
                            corresp="#p_CMGWC1">Chase</persName> to Gen. <persName>Peng
                            Meng-chi</persName>, Acting Chief of General Staff, dated Nov. 3, is in
                        Taipei Embassy files, lot 62 F 83.</note> today stating Tung An raid was in
                    violation of our understandings and I have made representations to acting
                    Foreign Minister today in same sense.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RKL1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Rankin</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
